hyp_text: The Great Pyramid of Giza was built by the pharaoh Khufu, and is the largest of the three pyramids in the Giza Necropolis. It is the oldest of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World, and the only one to remain largely intact. Based on a mark in an interior chamber naming the work gang and a reference to the Fourth Dynasty Egyptian pharaoh Khufu, some Egyptologists believe that the pyramid was thus built as a tomb over a 10- to 20-year period concluding around 2560 BC. Initially at 146.5 metres (481 feet), the Great Pyramid was the tallest man-made structure in the world for more than 3,800 years. Originally, the Great Pyramid was covered by limestone casing stones that formed a smooth outer surface; what is seen today is the underlying core structure. Some of the casing stones that once covered the structure can still be seen around the base. There have been varying scientific and alternative theories about the Great Pyramid's construction techniques. Most accepted construction hypotheses are based on the idea that it was built by moving huge stones from a quarry and dragging and lifting them into place. There are three known chambers inside the Great Pyramid. The lowest chamber is cut into the bedrock upon which the pyramid was built and was unfinished. The so-called Queen's Chamber and King's Chamber are higher up within the pyramid structure. The main part of the Giza complex is a set of buildings that included two mortuary temples in honour of Khufu (one close to the pyramid and one near the Nile), three smaller pyramids for Khufu's wives, an even smaller "satellite" pyramid, a raised causeway connecting the two temples, and small mastaba tombs surrounding the pyramid for nobles.

hyp_text: George Washington was born on February 22, 1732, in Westmoreland County, Virginia. Colonial Virginia’s economy was based on tobacco, and landowners such as Washington depended on the labor of enslaved Africans to work on their tobacco plantations. In 1759, he married Martha Dandridge Custis, a wealthy widow, thus adding to his land and slave holdings. He supported the nonimportation of British goods following the Stamp Act in 1765, which eventually led to a boycott of these goods in the colonies in 1767. The following year, Washington signed a petition written by George Mason to Virginia’s governor, complaining about taxation without representation. As tensions rose against the British and the American Revolution approached in the mid-1770s, Washington served as a delegate to the Continental Congress and was unanimously elected commander in chief of the Continental Army. On July 3, 1775, at Cambridge, Massachusetts, he took command of his ill-trained troops and embarked upon a war that lasted six grueling years. He led his army to victory in the Battle of Boston, and then to defeats at the hands of British General William Howe on Long Island, Manhattan, and across New Jersey. Yet he rallied his troops to a victory at Trenton, New Jersey, on Christmas Day by crossing the Delaware River under cover of night, and at Princeton, New Jersey, a week later. These victories reasserted American control of much of New Jersey and greatly improved the morale and unity of the colonial army and militia. In 1777, he forced the British to withdraw from the Delaware River, and defeated them at Saratoga, one of the most decisive battles of the American Revolution, and at Yorktown, Virginia, in 1781, the last major battle of the war. Washington, despite having little experience administrating large, conventional armies, was a pragmatic commander, more notable for his determination and ability to keep the army together than for his strategic brilliance. Washington’s civilian restraints over the military would later give rise to the United States’ strong tradition of civilian control of the military. In March 1783, Washington dramatically ended the Newburgh Conspiracy and forcefully asserted civilian authority over the military. At the end of the war, Washington retired to Mount Vernon, his plantation on the Potomac River in Virginia, and returned to the life of a planter and gentleman farmer. In 1787, he was persuaded to attend the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia and subsequently was unanimously elected its president. Although he is not known to have said much during the debates, he did, however, cast his considerable prestige toward the creation of a more empowered federal government whose executive was independent of the legislative branch, with veto power over it. After the convention, his support convinced many, including the reluctant Thomas Jefferson, that the Constitution should be ratified. On February 4, 1789, electors chose Washington to be the first president of the United States. He remains the only president to have received 100 percent of the electoral votes. Washington took the oath of office as the first President on April 30, 1789, at Federal Hall, New York. In the beginning, he relied heavily on Jefferson as the secretary of state and Alexander Hamilton as secretary of the treasury. Gouverneur Morris, minister to France, wrote Washington a description of the tearful farewell given to him by the people of Paris. The first president set many precedents, including the title “Mr. President,” the inauguration ceremony, messages to Congress, and the Cabinet form of government. Two days before he left office in March 1797, President Washington signed the law establishing the Library of Congress. In 1798, Washington was appointed lieutenant general and commander of the armies by President John Adams. He held the post until his death on December 14, 1799, at Mount Vernon. Washington was entombed in a family crypt he had built upon first inheriting the property. In 1831, the crypt was rebuilt and enlarged, and Washington’s remains were moved into the new tomb, without fanfare, on October 7. In 1832, Congress commissioned Horatio Greenough to construct a statue of Washington for display in the Capitol rotunda in Washington, D.C. In 1843, Greenough’s statue arrived from Italy. Weighing 18 tons, the statue rested on a massive pedestal. The work was controversial from the start. Many felt that a classical design was inappropriate for the father of the country. The statue was displayed on the east lawn of the Capitol where it was exposed to the elements and began to deteriorate. In 1908, the Joint Committee on the Library ordered the statue moved to the Capitol’s rotunda. It was placed in the crypt on a large glass pedestal. On the centennial of Washington’s death, on December 12, 1899, both houses of Congress assembled in the rotunda to honor his memory. On February 22, 1900, an elaborate program was held in the rotunda, which was draped in black and purple. The statue was moved to the Capitol’s Hall of Columns for the ceremony. The statue was returned to its pedestal in the rotunda in 1964, as recommended by the Architect of the Capitol. On September 18, 2001, a special joint meeting of Congress met in the Capitol to remember the victims of the terrorist attacks on the World Trade Center and the Pentagon one week earlier. On the evening of September 11, the statue had been draped with a black cloth in remembrance of the victims. The cloth was removed for the meeting. The statue was on view in the Capitol rotunda until 2008 when it was removed during the renovation of the Capitol Visitor Center. The statue was returned to the Capitol rotunda on September 19, 2013.
